
<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="subsec-analysis-of-the-general-second" >
    <title>Analysis of the General Second Degree Equations</title>


    <p>In the previous sections, we have seen that the equation of the form</p>

    <p><m>A x^2 + C y^2 + D x + E y + F = 0</m>.......... (1)</p>

    <p>represents a conic section (a parabola, ellipse, or hyperbola) whose axis of symmetry is parallel to one of the coordinate axes, except in degenerate cases.</p>

    <p>In Subsection 4.6.1, we also saw some examples of conic sections whose equations involve the <m>xy</m> term when their lines of symmetry are not parallel to either of the axes.</p>

    <p>Now we would like to analyze the graph of any quadratic (second degree) equation in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> of the form:</p>

    <p><m>A x^2 + B x y + C y^2 + D x + E y + F = 0</m>........... (2)</p>

    <p>where <m>B ≠ 0</m>. In order to analyze the graph of Equation (2), we usually convert it into an equation of type (1) using a suitable rotated coordinate system. To this end, we prove the following theorem.</p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-4analysis">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Consider the general second degree equation:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>A x^2 + B x y + C y^2 + D x + E y + F = 0</m>, where <m>B ≠ 0</m> ........... (2)
            </p>
            <p>
                There exists a rotation angle <m>θ ∈ (0, π/2)</m> such that, after rotating the <m>xy</m>-coordinate system by this angle, the equation becomes:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>A' x'^2 + C' y'^2 + D' x' + E' y' + F' = 0</m>........... (3)
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    
 
    <p> <m>\textbf{Proof:}</m> Let the <m>xy</m>-coordinate system be rotated by an angle <m>θ</m> about the origin to form a new <m>x'y'</m>-coordinate system. Then, from the rotation formula (3),we have </p> 
    <p>
        <me>
            x=x'cos\theta -y'sin\theta \,\, \text{and} \, \, y=x'sin\theta +y'cos\theta 
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p> we substitute for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in Equation (2) so that </p>
    <p>
        <me>
            A\left ( x'cos\theta -y'sin\theta\right)^{2} +B\left ( x'cos\theta -y'cos\theta  \right )\left ( x'sin\theta +y'cos\theta  \right ) +C\left ( x'sin\theta +ycos'\theta  \right )^{2} +D\left ( x'cos\theta -y'sin\theta  \right )+E\left ( x'sin\theta +y'cos\theta  \right )+F=0 
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        After some calculations, combining like terms (those involving <m>x'_2,x'y',y'_2</m> and so on ), we get
        equation of the form
    </p>

    <p><m>A' x'^2 + B' x' y' + C' y'^2 + D' x' + E' y' + F' = 0</m>............... (4)</p>

    <p>where the new coefficient <m>B'</m> is given by:</p>

    <p><m>B' = 2(C − A) sin(θ) cos(θ) + B (cos^2(θ) − sin^2(θ))</m></p>

    <p>
        Here the exact expressions for A', C', D', E' are omitted as they are irrelevant. What we
        need is to get the angle of rotation <m>\theta</m> for which Equation (4) has no x'y' term, that is B'=0.
    </p>
    <p>
        This means that,
        <me>
            2(C − A) sin(θ) cos(θ) + B (cos^2(θ) − sin^2(θ))=0
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        Since <m>2 sin(θ) cos(θ) = sin2(θ)</m> and   <m>cos^2(θ) + B  − sin^2(θ)=cos2θ</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        this equation is equivalent to 
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
            (C − A) sin(2θ) + B cos(2θ) = 0
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        or <me>
            \frac{\text{cos}2\theta}{\text{sin}2\theta}=\frac{A-C}{B}, \text{Since} B \neq  0
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        or <me>
            \text{cot}2\theta=\frac{A-C}{B} .......(5)
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        That is, if we choose the angle of rotation  satisfying (5), then B' = 0 in Equation (4) 
         so that the resulting equation in x'y'-coordinate system is in the form of Equation (3).
         Moreover, we can always find an angle that satisfies <m>\text{cot}2\theta=\frac{A-C}{B}</m> for any A C, <m>\text{B}\epsilon \Re , \text{B}\neq 0</m>
         since the range of the cotangent function is the entire set of real numbers.
         Note also that since <m>2\theta \epsilon (0,\pi )</m>, the angel of rotation  can always be chosen so that <m>0&lt; \theta &lt; \frac{\pi}{2}</m>. So, the Theorem is proved. 
    </p>



    <remark>
    <p>
      If <m>A = C</m>, then
      <m>\frac{\cos 2\theta}{\sin 2\theta} = \frac{A - C}{B} = 0 \Rightarrow 2\theta = \frac{\pi}{2} \Rightarrow \theta = \frac{\pi}{4}</m>.
    </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
        Therefore, we can rewrite the result of the above theorem as follows:
    </p>

    <p>
        The rotation of the <m>xy</m>-coordinate system by angle <m>\theta</m> creates an <m>x'y'</m>-coordinate system in which a general second degree equation 
        <m>Ax^2 + Bxy + Cy^2 + Dx + Ey + F = 0</m>, with <m>B \ne 0</m>,
        is converted to an equation 
        <m>A'x'^2 + C'y'^2 + D'x' + E'y' + F' = 0</m> (with no <m>x'y'</m> term),
        if we choose <m>\theta \in (0, \frac{\pi}{2})</m> such that:
    </p>

    <p>
        <m>\tan 2\theta = \frac{B}{A - C}, \text{ if } A \ne C</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\theta = \frac{\pi}{4}, \text{ if } \text{A = C}</m>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Use rotation of axes to eliminate the <m>xy</m> term in the equation
            <m>8x^2 + 8y^2 + 28xy - 32x - 32y + 30 = 0</m>,
            describe the locus (type of conic section), and sketch the graph.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given: <m>8x^2 + 8y^2 + 28xy - 32x - 32y + 30 = 0</m>
                            <m>\Rightarrow A = C = 8</m>. So from the above remark, <m>\theta = \frac{\pi}{4}</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Then <m>\cos \theta = \sin \theta = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>,
                            so the transformation is:
                            <m>x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(x' - y')</m>, <m>y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(x' + y')</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Substituting into the original equation and simplifying, we obtain:
                            <m>8x'^2 - 16y' + 8 = 0</m> or <m>(y' - 2)^2 = x'</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            This is an equation of a parabola with vertex at <m>(0,2)</m> in the <m>x'y'</m> system,
                            and axis along the <m>y'</m>-axis, opening in the negative <m>y'</m>direction.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="analytic-geometry1">
                            <caption></caption>
                            <image source="/rotation-of-coordinates3.png">
                                <shortdescription>(for accessibility)</shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given: <m>73x^2 - 72xy + 52y^2 + 30x + 40y - 75 = 0</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Here <m>A = 73</m>, <m>B = -72</m>, <m>C = 52</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Hence <m>\tan 2\theta = \frac{B}{A - C} = \frac{-72}{73 - 52} = -\frac{72}{21} = -\frac{24}{7}</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            So terminal side of <m>2\theta</m> is in 2nd quadrant, through <m>(-7,24)</m>.
                            Hence <m>\cos 2\theta = -\frac{7}{25}</m>. Then
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <m>\cos \theta = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos 2\theta}{2}} = \sqrt{\frac{1 - 7/25}{2}} = \sqrt{\frac{18}{50}} = \frac{3}{5}</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <m>\sin \theta = \sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \theta} = \frac{4}{5}</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            So the rotation is:
                            <m>x = \frac{3}{5}x' - \frac{4}{5}y'</m>, <m>y = \frac{4}{5}x' + \frac{3}{5}y'</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Substituting and simplifying, we get:
                            <m>25x'^2 + 100x' - 50y' + 75 = 0</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Completing the square and dividing by 100 to get
                            <m>\frac{(x' + 2)^2}{4} + \frac{y'}{1} = 1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            which is an ellipse with center at <m>(h',k') = (-1, 0)</m> relative to the <m>x'y'</m>-system, major axis on <m>x'</m>-
                            axis (which is the line <m>y = \frac{4}{3}x</m> ), length of major axis = 4 and length of minor axis = 2. (You
                            can show that the center is <m>(h, k) =\left( -\frac{3}{5}, -\frac{4}{5} \right)</m> relative to the <m>xy</m>-system).
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="analytic-geometry2">
                            <caption></caption>
                            <image source="/rotation-of-coordinates4.png">
                                <shortdescription>(for accessibility)</shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </figure>

                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-analysis-of-the-general">
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                     Find an equation of the conic section having the given properties and sketch its graph.
                     <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Ellipsi with center at origin, foci at <m>(-2,2)</m> and <m>(2, 2)</m>, and length of major axis <m>2\sqrt{8}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Parabola whose vertex is at <m>(3, 4)</m> and focus <m>(-5,-2)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Hyperbola whose foci are <m>(-2, 2)</m> and <m>(2, -2)</m>, and length of transverse axis <m>2\sqrt{2}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                     </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use rotation of axes to eliminate the <m>xy</m> term in each of the following equations, describe the
                    locus (type of conic section) and sketch the graph of the equation.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                 <m>17x^2 - 12xy + 8y^2 - 36 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>8x^2 + 24xy + y^2 - 1 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                 <m>x^2 - 2xy + y^2 - 5y = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                 <m>2x^2 + xy = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>5x^2 + 6xy + 5y^2 - 4x + 4y - 4 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>x^2 + 4xy + 4y^2 + 2x - 2y + 1 = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that if <m>B &gt; 0</m>, then the graph of
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        x^2 + 2Bxy = F
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    is a hyperbola if <m>F \ne 0</m>, and two intersecting lines if <m>F = 0</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>


